<subSubSection id="D48C652EFFCCFF8AFA889932F886FDD6" box="[1297,1818,558,625]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262" type="vernacular_names">(MONGOOSES)</subSubSection>
</paragraph>
<subSubSection id="D48C652EFFCCFF8AFB7A99A4F85BFA8F" pageId="0" pageNumber="262" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="9C2936A5FFCCFF8AFB7A99A4F79AFC8F" blockId="0.[1249,2131,696,1330]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">
• Smallsized mammals with relatively uniform morphology characterized by a long face 
<emphasis id="AEE2EAB7FFCCFF8AF89499FCF8DAFCA6" bold="true" box="[1805,1862,736,769]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">and</emphasis>
body, short legs, 
<emphasis id="AEE2EAB7FFCCFF8AFA91981BFACAFC8F" bold="true" box="[1288,1366,775,808]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">small</emphasis>
rounded ears, and long, tapering 
<emphasis id="AEE2EAB7FFCCFF8AF8FA981BF820FC8F" bold="true" box="[1891,1980,775,808]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">bushy</emphasis>
tails.
</paragraph>
<caption id="C8E9662DFFCCFF8AFB7A9833FA2EFCF7" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6347102" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6347102" box="[1251,1458,815,848]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6347102/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="262" targetBox="[1512,1929,833,1041]" targetPageId="0">
<paragraph id="9C2936A5FFCCFF8AFB7A9833FA2EFCF7" blockId="0.[1249,2131,696,1330]" box="[1251,1458,815,848]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">
• 34 
<emphasis id="AEE2EAB7FFCCFF8AFAA39833FAEDFCF7" bold="true" box="[1338,1393,815,848]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">-151</emphasis>
cm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="C8E9662DFFCCFF8AFB7D9F06F88AFBC4" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6347104" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6347104" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6347104/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="262" targetBox="[237,1182,703,1329]" targetPageId="0">
<paragraph id="9C2936A5FFCCFF8AFB7D9F06F88AFBC4" blockId="0.[1249,2131,696,1330]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">
• Old 
<emphasis id="AEE2EAB7FFCCFF8AFACD9F06FA2FFB9C" bold="true" box="[1364,1459,1050,1083]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">World</emphasis>
tropics throughout Asia and Africa, also 
<emphasis id="AEE2EAB7FFCCFF8AFA909F5EFAE8FBC4" bold="true" box="[1289,1396,1090,1123]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">Middle</emphasis>
East and southern Europe.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="9C2936A5FFCCFF8AFB7C9F75F7D4FB7E" blockId="0.[1249,2131,696,1330]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">• Found in habitats ranging from open areas, such as deserts, savannah, and grasslands, to closed forest, over a wide elevation range, from lowlands to montane areas.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C2936A5FFCCFF8AFB7D9FF8F837FAA6" blockId="0.[1249,2131,696,1330]" box="[1252,1963,1252,1281]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">• 15 genera, 34 species, at least 84 extant taxa.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C2936A5FFCCFF8AFB7C9E17F85BFA8F" blockId="0.[1249,2131,696,1330]" box="[1253,1991,1291,1320]" pageId="0" pageNumber="262">• 2 species Vulnerable; none Extinct since 1600.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
